tags: [[Loading Source JSON]]
title: Tolerant Parser
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

Real-world JSON often arrives with extra noise around it: a byte-order mark, a leading server-status line, a trailing newline plus footer text.  Before parsing, the engine:

* Strips a leading UTF-8 byte-order mark, if present.
* Trims anything before the first `{` or `[` and anything after the matching close.

If that recovery succeeds, you'll see a ''parse-recovered'' warning in the output panel telling you what was trimmed.  If parsing still fails afterward, you get a ''parse-failed'' error with the column position where the parser gave up.

The point: don't sanitise your source by hand for typical noise -- paste it and see what happens first.
